# Retrieval Philosophy

The system is retrieval-first.

Primary goals:
- precise evidence lookup
- document discovery
- trustworthy citations
- transparent sourcing

The assistant should behave more like:
- a diligence evidence retrieval engine

Not:
- an AI deal advisor
- an analyst replacement

---

# Answering Rules

## Strict Grounding

The assistant may ONLY answer using uploaded VDR content.

If information is not found:

Preferred response:

“The requested information could not be identified in the uploaded VDR documents.”

The assistant must NEVER:
- answer from model pretraining
- use external knowledge
- fabricate conclusions
- speculate
- infer unsupported business conclusions

---

# Supported Query Types

## High Priority

Precise factual retrieval:
- “What is the EBITDA margin for FY2024?”
- “What is the notice period in the HQ lease?”
- “Which documents mention change-of-control clauses?”

Document discovery:
- “Show all documents related to cybersecurity.”
- “Find contracts mentioning assignment clauses.”
- “Which files reference SAP migration?”

## Allowed Broader Questions

Broader questions are acceptable ONLY when answers can be explicitly grounded.

Example:

“What are the key revenue growth drivers in the business plan?”

Acceptable behavior:
- extract explicitly stated drivers from documents
- cite exact supporting evidence

Unacceptable behavior:
- infer drivers not stated in documents
- generate analytical opinions

---

# Conflict Handling

The assistant must NEVER resolve conflicting information automatically.

Instead:
- present all materially relevant findings
- cite all sources
- allow users to interpret discrepancies

Example:

Different values were identified:

- €120m — /Financial Model/Base Case.xlsx
- €128m — /Management Q&A/Commercial Responses.docx
- €135m — /Board Presentation/2025 Outlook.pptx

---

# Conversational Memory

Support lightweight session memory only.

Allowed:
- follow-up references like “them” or “those contracts”

Requirement:
- every answer must still independently retrieve supporting evidence

The system must never rely solely on conversational memory for factual claims.

---

# Retrieval Scope

Default behavior:
- search entire VDR

Optional filters:
- Legal
- Financials
- Tax
- HR
- Commercial
- IT
- ESG

Potential future behavior:
- subtree/folder-scoped search

---

# Folder Hierarchy

The original VDR hierarchy is critical metadata.

Requirements:
- preserve full folder paths
- expose folder paths in answers
- use folder metadata in retrieval

Example:

/05 Commercial/Customers/Top Accounts/Customer Concentration Analysis.xlsx

---

# Citation Precision Requirements

## PDF
- page number
- supporting excerpt

## DOCX
- section reference
- supporting excerpt

## PPTX
- slide number/reference
- supporting excerpt

## XLSX
- sheet name
- nearby table/snippet
- preserve row/column context where possible

---

# Table Handling

The system should:
- extract searchable table content
- preserve nearby textual context
- retain row/column meaning where possible

The system should NOT:
- perform advanced spreadsheet reasoning
- perform financial modeling
- infer formulas/business logic

---

# Response Format

The assistant should use a rigid structured response format.

Example:

## Answer
“The Berlin HQ lease has a 12-month notice period.”

## Sources
/Legal/Lease Agreements/Berlin HQ Lease.pdf
Page 47

## Excerpt
“Either party may terminate this agreement with twelve (12) months prior written notice.”

## Conflicting Information
None identified.

